==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|lang=fro|noise||a dispute, wrangle, strife, noise}}; origin uncertain; according to some, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|nausea|lang=la||disgust, nausea}}; according to others, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|lang=la|noxia||hurt, harm, damage, injury}}; but neither explanation is satisfactory in regard to either form or sense.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|noiz}}, {{IPA|/nɔɪz/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/nOIz/}}
* {{audio|en-us-noise.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|En-uk-noise.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|ɔɪz}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Various sounds, usually unwanted.
#: ''He knew that it was trash day, when the garbage collectors made all the '''noise'''.''
# Sound or signal generated by random [[fluctuation]]s
# {{technology}} Unwanted part of a [[signal]]. (''[[signal-to-noise ratio|Signal to noise ratio]]'')
# {{genetics}} The measured level of variation in [[gene]] expression among cells, regardless of source, within a supposedly identical population
# [[rumour]] or [[complaint]]
#: ''The problems with the new computer system are causing a lot of '''noise''' at Head Office.''

